subSubSection.paragraph:
Skeleton.
Plumose architecture (
Fig. 7A
). Ectosomal region with tornotes in bundles (up to 12 spicules) and in bouquets, which rarely protrude to the surface, up to 50 µm high (Figs. B–D). Ectosomal acanthostyles in tangential to paratangential arrangement at the surface making a continuous layer, ca. 50 µm thick (
Figs. 7D–F
). Choanosomal region with tornotes in tracts (up to 12 spicules). Thick tracts of choanosomal acanthostyles (more than 15 spicules) at the base of the choanosome. Several ectosomal acanthostyles and arcuate isochelae occur scattered throughout the choanosome. All categories of acanthostyles (ectosomal and choanosomal) are distinguished by size (length and width) and patterns of spination. In spongin there are wide rounded subectosomal (150–700 µm longer length) and choanosomal channels (ca. 1000 µm longer length). No spongin fibers.
